\begin_layout Subsection*
Lotteries, Expected Utility, and Risk Aversion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Examples - Literal Lotteries
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
State Lotteries sold $53 billion of lottery tickets in 2010.
 Suppose the cost of playing is $1 and the expected value of playing is
 50 cents (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{i}p_{i}W_{i}=\$0.50$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{i}$
\end_inset

 is payout 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 is probability of that payout).
 Mr.
 Jo, a VNM expected utility maximizer, is indifferent between playing the
 lottery or not.
 Is Mr.
 Jo risk-averse, risk-loving, neither, or is there not enough information
 to say? Explain.
 
\begin_inset Separator latexpar
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution.
 
\shape italic
\emph default
Mr.
 Jo's certainty equivalent of playing the lottery is $1 (since he is indifferent
 between playing or not), so 
\begin_inset Formula $CE[Lottery]>EV[Lottery]$
\end_inset

 and the risk premium is 
\begin_inset Formula $-50$
\end_inset

 cents.
 This makes Mr.
 Jo a risk-lover (even though he may not actually play the lottery).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider the following lotteries:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
$100 with certainty 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
$200 with probability 0.7; $0 with probability 0.3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
$110 with certainty 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
$1200 with probability 0.1; $0 with probability 0.9
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
$200 with probability 0.35; $100 with probability 0.5; $0 with probability
 0.15
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
$1200 with probability 0.05; $110 with probability 0.5; $0 with probability
 0.45
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate-Resume
Suppose Bob is indifferent between lottery (a) and lottery (b).
 He is also indifferent between lottery (c) and lottery (d).
 Is Bob risk-averse, risk-loving, risk-neutral or is it impossible to say?
 Explain your answer.
 
\begin_inset Separator latexpar
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution.

\series bold
 
\series default
The expected value to lottery (b) is $140.
 Bob is indifferent between lottery (a), that provides $100 with certainty
 and lottery (b), that provides a higher amount, $140, in expectation but
 with uncertainty.
 This must mean that he is risk-averse in this choice.
 The same conclusion follow if we examine his choice between lottery (c)
 and (d).
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Cynthia has same choices as Bob.
 She is indifferent between lotteries (a) and (b) and between lotteries
 (c) and (d).
 If Cynthia is an expected utility maximizer and her utility is increasing
 in money/wealth, which lottery will she pick when faced with a choice between
 lotteries (e) and (f)?
\series bold

\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series default
\emph on
Solution.
 Note that lottery (e) a convex combination of lotteries (a) and (b): It
 offers lottery (a) with 50% probability and lottery (b) with 50% probability.
 Since Cynthia is indifferent between lotteries (a) and (b), lottery (e)
 is equivalent to lottery (a).
 Similarly, lottery (f) is a convex combination of lotteries (c) and (d)
 and is therefore equivalent to lottery (c).
 As Cynthia's utility is increasing in wealth, she prefers lottery (c) to
 (a).
 Therefore, she will pick lottery (f) to lottery (e).
 More formally, Cynthia's choice between lotteries (a) and (b) and lotteries
 (c) and (d) imply that (normalizing Cynthia's initial wealth level to 0)
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}u\left(100\right)= & 0.7u\left(200\right)+0.3u\left(0\right)\\
\implies0.5u\left(100\right)= & 0.35u\left(200\right)+0.15u\left(0\right)
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}u\left(110\right)= & 0.1u\left(1200\right)+0.9u\left(0\right)\\
\implies0.5u\left(110\right)= & 0.05u\left(1200\right)+0.45u\left(0\right)
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

Now, the expected utility from lottery (e) is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned} & 0.35u\left(200\right)+0.5u\left(100\right)+0.15u\left(0\right)\\
= & 0.5u\left(100\right)+0.5u\left(100\right)\\
= & u\left(100\right)
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

The expected utility from lottery (f) is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned} & 0.05u\left(1200\right)+0.5u\left(110\right)+0.45u\left(0\right)\\
= & 0.5u\left(110\right)+0.5u\left(110\right)\\
= & u\left(110\right)
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

Since Cynthia's utility is increasing in wealth 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u\left(110\right)>u\left(100\right)
\]

\end_inset

so she will pick lottery (f).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Example - Startup Insurance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following the increase in the number of MIT graduates who start new companies
 and given the inherent risks of starting a company, Cambridge Savings Bank
 offers insurance to startup companies with more than 5 employees.
 Before the startup hires any employees, the startup's founder has to invest
 
\begin_inset Formula $\$100,000$
\end_inset

 in equipment.
 Throughout the question, assume that the initial wealth of startup founders
 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{0}=\$150,000$
\end_inset

 and that they are risk-averse with a VNM utility function over wealth that
 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $u(w)=\ln(w)$
\end_inset

.
 A startup becomes the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

next Uber
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=.05$
\end_inset

, resulting in a net gain of 
\begin_inset Formula $\$19,850,000$
\end_inset

 to its founder (so the total wealth of the founder if the startup is successful
 will be 20 million dollars); with probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\pi$
\end_inset

, the startup goes bust, resulting in the loss of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\$100,000$
\end_inset

 invested in equipment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The startup insurance offered by Cambridge Savings Bank looks as follows:
 The bank offers to pay the startup 
\begin_inset Formula $\$1$
\end_inset

 if it goes bust in exchange for receiving 
\begin_inset Formula $\$S$
\end_inset

 dollars if the startup is successful.
 What should the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be for the insurance to be considered actuarially fair?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution.
 
\emph default
The expected return to the bank of this contract is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi S-(1-\pi)$
\end_inset

.
 For the insurance to be actuarially fair, this expected return must be
 equal to zero; that is,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=\frac{1-\pi}{\pi}=\frac{.95}{.05}=19.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
How much startup insurance do startup founders buy if 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is chosen as in the previous part?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution.

\emph default
 
\shape italic
Suppose the startup founder buys 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 units of insurance.
 Then his/her expected utility is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi\ln(20M-19x)+(1-\pi)\ln(50,000+x).
\]

\end_inset

The startup founder chooses 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to maximize this expression.
 We can solve this problem by taking the FOC with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\frac{19\pi}{20M-19x}+\frac{(1-\pi)}{50,000+x}=0.
\]

\end_inset

Noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $19\pi=1-\pi$
\end_inset

, we can immediately see that it must be that 
\begin_inset Formula $20M-19x=50,000+x$
\end_inset

, which implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $x=997,500$
\end_inset

.
 Regardless of whether the startup succeeds, the founder will have 
\begin_inset Formula $20M-19\cdot997,500=50,000+997,500=1,047,500$
\end_inset

 dollars in wealth.
 This is a more general principle: risk-averse agents always purchase full
 insurance if they are offered insurance at the actuarially fair price.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose that every MIT graduate who starts a company also buys startup insurance
 (to the extent that you found in the previous part).
 Are MIT graduates better off starting companies (and buying startup insurance)
 or not starting a company at all (and keeping their 
\begin_inset Formula $\$150,000$
\end_inset

 to themselves)?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution.

\shape italic
\emph default
 The payoff to the founder from starting a company and buying full insurance
 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln(1,047,500)$
\end_inset

, whereas if they don't start start a company their payoff will be 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln(150,000)$
\end_inset

.
 So MIT graduates are better off starting companies and buying insurance.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
A new deep learning algorithm can analyze a startup immediately after the
 
\begin_inset Formula $\$100,000$
\end_inset

 investment in equipment has been made to determine whether the startup
 will be a success or not.
 The algorithm's output is posted on a publicly-accessible online database.
 Who will buy insurance in equilibrium after the introduction of the algorithm?
 [Hint: The output of the algorithm will be publicly visible 
\emph on
before
\emph default
 the startup hires any employees and so before it is eligible for insurance.
 Assume that Cambridge Savings Bank cannot reject any customers but it can
 adjust 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 in response to changes in the set of customers who buy insurance.]
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution.

\shape italic
\emph default
 Since all the uncertainty is resolved after the output of the algorithm
 is observed, there are no insurance opportunities left: as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $S>0$
\end_inset

, only startups founders whose companies will not be successful will buy
 insurance.
 But if that's the case, then no contract (with finite 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

) would be actuarially fair.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
How does your answer to part (3) change as a result of the advent of the
 algorithm?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution.

\emph default
 
\shape italic
Given that there are no longer any opportunities to buy insurance, the expected
 utility of an MIT graduate from starting a company is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\ln(20M)+(1-\pi)\ln(50,000)\approx11.120$
\end_inset

, whereas their expected payoff from not starting a company is given by
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln(150,000)\approx11.918$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, MIT graduates are better off not starting a company.
 This problem shows that more information can lead to a decrease in welfare
 if it is provided at an interim stage (when investments are made but the
 risky output has not yet to realize).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection*
Regression Discontinuity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Example - Saving Babies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Medical expenditures in the United States are high and increasing.
 A key policy question is, therefore, whether the benefits of additional
 medical expenditures exceed their costs.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note: this question is based on the paper 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Estimating marginal returns to medical care: evidence from at-risk newborns,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by Douglas Almond, Joseph Doyle, Amanda Kowalski, and Heidi Williams, 
\emph on
Quarterly Journal of Economics
\emph default
, 2011.
 It is not necessary to read the paper to answer this question.
 But it is a terrific paper to read.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be a health outcome of newborns (for example, one-year mortality), and
 
\begin_inset Formula $(Y_{0},Y_{1})$
\end_inset

 be the potential outcomes when the newborn does not receive intensive medical
 treatment (
\begin_inset Formula $T=0$
\end_inset

) and when the newborn receives intensive medical treatment (
\begin_inset Formula $T=1$
\end_inset

).
 Explain in words and show mathematically why comparing 
\begin_inset Formula $E[Y|T=1]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E[Y|T=0]$
\end_inset

 would not be a good idea to estimate the causal effect of intensive medical
 treatment on health outcomes of newborns.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution.
 
\shape italic
\emph default
We might have a problem of omitted variables that are correlated with both
 intensive treatment and health outcomes.
 In this example, newborns that have a higher risk probably receive more
 intensive treatment.
 Mathematically:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E[Y|T=1]-E[Y|T=0]=E[Y_{1}|T=1]-E[Y_{0}|T=0]=E[Y_{1}-Y_{0}|T=1]+\{E[Y_{0}|T=1]-E[Y_{0}|T=0]\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\shape italic
In a 2011 paper, Douglas Almond, Joseph Doyle, Amanda Kowalski, and Heidi
 Williams estimate the causal effect of intensive medical treatment on the
 health outcomes of low birth weight newborns using a regression discontinuity
 approach.
 When a newborn weighs less than 
\begin_inset Formula $1,500g$
\end_inset

, he/she is classified as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

very low birth weight
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (VLBW).
 Newborns classified as VLBW are more likely to receive Intensive Medical
 Treatment (IMT), such as admission to neonatal intensive care, ventilation,
 incubation, etc.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 be a dummy variable equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 if a newborn is classified as VLBW, and 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 otherwise.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}$
\end_inset

 be the birth weight of a newborn.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=1$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}<1,500$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z=0$
\end_inset

 otherwise.
 Would it be a good idea to use 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 as an instrument for 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 to estimate the causal effect of intensive medical treatment on health
 outcomes? Which IV identification assumption might be invalid?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Solution.
 
\shape italic
\emph default
This would not be a good idea.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 would satisfy one IV condition, because it is correlated with IMT.
 However, newborns with 
\begin_inset Formula $T=1$
\end_inset

 would have lower birth weight than newborns with 
\begin_inset Formula $T=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since birth weight might have an independent effect on health outcomes,
 the exclusion restriction would not be satisfied.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Instead, the authors use the discontinuity at 
