\begin_layout Itemize
A set of wages for agents without and with schooling 
\begin_inset Formula $W(S=0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W(S=1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Start by assuming that we have a separating equilibrium.
 Then,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
W(S=0) & =E[a\vert S=0]=0\\
W(S=1) & =E[a\vert S=1]=1.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is this a truly a separating equilibrium, or will one type want to deviate?
 Compare the payoffs from school and no school for both types of agents.
 For the 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 type:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\textrm{no school: }u(W(S=0),0) & =0-0=0\\
\textrm{school: }u(W(S=1),c(a_{H})) & =1-\frac{3}{2}(1-a_{H})=1
\end{align*}

\end_inset

For the 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 type:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\textrm{no school: }u(W(S=0),0) & =0-0=0\\
\textrm{school: }u(W(S=1),c(a_{L})) & =1-\frac{3}{2}(1-a_{L})=-\frac{1}{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So nobody will want to deviate.
 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 prefers school, 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 prefers no school.
\end_layout

