\begin_inset Formula $U[\cdot]$
\end_inset

 is the uniform distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Productivity is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(a)=a$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Before entering the workforce, agents can choose to obtain schooling 
\begin_inset Formula $S\in\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

.
 Schooling is costly, but less costly if you are high ability.
 Let the cost be given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c(a)=k(1-a)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The labor market is competitive, so firms pay employees their expected productiv
ity.
 Wages are given by 
\begin_inset Formula $W(S=0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W(S=1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The agents' utility is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(W,c)=W-c.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Separating Equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\frac{3}{4}$
\end_inset

.
 We are looking for an equilibrium that consists of:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A cutoff value 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{*}$
\end_inset

, above which agents will choose 
\begin_inset Formula $S=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A set of wages for agents without and with schooling 
\begin_inset Formula $W(S=0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W(S=1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Start by just assuming that we have a separating equilibrium, with a cutoff
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
W(S=0) & =E[a\vert S=0]=E[a\vert a\leq a^{*}]=\frac{a^{*}}{2}\\
W(S=1) & =E[a\vert S=1]=E[a\vert a>a^{*}]=\frac{1+a^{*}}{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Next, solve for the cutoff 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 We want to find the agent who is indifferent between schooling and no schooling
:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\underbrace{W(S=0)-0}_{\textrm{utility from no school}} & =\underbrace{W(S=1)-c(a^{*})}_{\textrm{utility from school}}\\
\frac{a^{*}}{2}-0 & =\frac{1+a^{*}}{2}-\frac{3}{4}\left(1-a^{*}\right)\\
0 & =\frac{1}{2}-\frac{3}{4}+\frac{3}{4}a^{*}\\
\frac{3}{4}a^{*} & =\frac{1}{4}\\
a^{*} & =\frac{1}{3}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Plugging in 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{*}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $W(S=0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W(S=1)$
\end_inset

 gives us
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
W(S=0) & =\frac{1}{6}\\
W(S=1) & =\frac{2}{3}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Finally, we need to check whether this is a separating equilibrium.
 Will anyone want to deviate? Compare the payoffs from school and no school:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\textrm{no school: }u(W(S=0),0) & =\frac{1}{6}-0=\frac{1}{6}\\
\textrm{school: }u(W(S=1),c(a)) & =\frac{2}{3}-\frac{3}{4}(1-a)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\frac{1}{3}-\epsilon$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 someone just below the cutoff), then the utility from school is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{2}{3}-\frac{3}{4}(1-\frac{1}{3}+\epsilon) & =\frac{2}{3}-\frac{3}{4}(1-\frac{1}{3}+\epsilon)\\
 & =\frac{2}{3}-\frac{3}{4}(\frac{2}{3}+\epsilon)\\
 & =\frac{1}{6}-\frac{3}{4}\epsilon<\frac{1}{6}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so this person will prefer 
\begin_inset Formula $S=0$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\frac{1}{3}+\epsilon$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 someone just above the cutoff), then the utility from school is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{2}{3}-\frac{3}{4}(1-\frac{1}{3}-\epsilon) & =\frac{2}{3}-\frac{3}{4}(1-\frac{1}{3}-\epsilon)\\
 & =\frac{2}{3}-\frac{3}{4}(\frac{2}{3}-\epsilon)\\
 & =\frac{1}{6}+\frac{3}{4}\epsilon>\frac{1}{6}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so this person will prefer 
\begin_inset Formula $S=1$
\end_inset

.
 So nobody will want to deviate.
 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 prefers school, 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 prefers no school.
\end_layout

